A long-legged ground-dweller that can reach a top speed of 30kmh Enigmatic ‘sailing’ stones Racetrack Playa Mesquite Flat Sand Dunes • Devil’s Hole (an off-site extension of Death Valley National Park Panamint Range Golden Canyon Badwater Dante’s View Amargosa Range • Rocks – some weighing over 300kg – appear to move across a dried lake bed known as Racetrack Playa on their own, leaving trails behind them in the cracked mud.
In 2013, for the first time, scientists filmed the movement of the stones using time-lapse photograph­y. Below is the explanatio­n of the rare phenomenon. Black-tailed jackrabbit Devil’s Hole pupfish Blood vessels in the ears act like a car radiator to dissipate heat (Cyprinodon diabolis) • (Lepus californic­us) • Found near valley floor and in mountains
Named for its ears, which resemble those of a jackass, or donkey
